snippet.title: Paris 5th Arrondissement - 20 in 20 Day 5 - Jardin des Plantes, Pantheon, and Rue Mouffetard
snippet.description:
Paris' 5th arrondissement is delightfully chill - a bit of the Jardin des Plantes, Rue Mouffetard, and the Pantheon to boot. Grab my guide to Paris here: http://bit.ly/ParisVloggersGuide for over 200 recommendations of places I know and love along with lots more information.

 Help me make better videos at http://patreon.com/jayswanson and then find me on the internet in all of the usual spots:

More swag here:
http://bit.ly/ShirtOfTheMonth (shirts and hat)
http://bit.ly/JaysGearList (my gear and books)
https://gum.co/camerafour (Disposable Camera Four digital scans)

Follow me here:
http://twitter.com/jayonaboat
http://instagram.com/jayswanson

Music by: David Cutter Music - http://www.davidcuttermusic.co.uk

My name is Jay Swanson - I'm an American writer living in Paris on an artist visa and hoping to make the city of light my home base - at least for the foreseeable future. I write science-fiction and fantasy, vlog daily, and love pizza a little too much.

Links below to Amazon are affiliate links - meaning if you click through them and buy something, I'll get some pennies. Thanks! (The FTC wants me to tell you that up front)

FAQ:
How long have you lived in France? On and off for over two years.

What do you miss most about ho- NACHOS

You're always talking about living on some ship. WHAT SHIP? - I made a "Draw My Life" video that explains a lot here: https://youtu.be/-MrvL37jTKM

Where are you from originally? - Pullman, Washington - a small university/agricultural town near Idaho (and yes, the potatoes are amazing).

What do you film with? - I've made a lot of changes recently, but I try to keep my gear list up to date if you want to see what I use and buy some for yourself: http://bit.ly/JaysGearList

What do you edit with? - Adobe Premiere - it's pretty much all I've ever used since high school.

Aren't you ever freaked out by leaving your camera behind to film yourself? - Yep. But not too badly - I tend to be careful when I do.

Why are you living in #Paris? - Because I've always wanted to; I feel at home here: https://youtu.be/4Vivf6MqMxQ

Do you speak French? Oui. https://youtu.be/va1QjaHgij8

You talk a lot about the books you're working on, what are they about? - They're sci-fi (and fantasy) and I've got a decent pitch for you here: https://youtu.be/W2bKt4_Tp4E

Do you make money off YouTube? - Ha, no. I wish. It took me over 500 videos to make my first total $100 off adsense. I think it will slowly change, but VERY slowly.

I really enjoy your videos, how can I support you? - The easiest and best way to support me is through Patreon, where you can pitch in as little as $1/mo to help me make better videos: http://patreon.com/jayswanson

I don't trust this Patreon thing - can I just paypal you? - Here's my ko-fi if that's your thing (and coffee is your game): https://ko-fi.com/jayswanson

But I want to send you something tangible! - I do have a wishlist on Amazon, though it's a bit complicated with the international shipping situation. This is the US one: http://amzn.to/2ykS9Ux

And here's the French wishlist: http://bit.ly/JaysFrenchWishList

Thanks for watching!

comments.textDisplay:
A few years back we rented an apartment on Rue Gracieuse, very close to the Place Monge and Rue Mouffetard. It's a great neighborhood, and the Place Monge market is wonderful if you have access to a kitchen and like to cook. It's a great thing to look out your window and see one of the iconic Parisian sites, but, at a certain point, a taste of the quotidian Parisian life becomes equally attractive. (That's one reason this vlog is so appealing.) For example, there was a vide-grenier in the neighborhood during our stay.

Last year I reread Le père Goriot in French and was surprised to learn that our little apartment was very close to where Goriot lived. Balzac's description of the area is not complimentary.

comments.textDisplay:
Congratulations on your 500th invader!!

Holy smokes, you had never been in Square René Viviani! I love that little park. Besides the great view of the Nôtre Dame, there are some of the carved stones from Nôtre Dame in there. The oldest tree in Paris is in there. Next time go to the back of the park and they saved an old well. It’s another pretty photo spot. In front of the church next to the park there are old stones from the Roman road. That church is the second oldest church in Paris.

When I was in Paris in January I went to Circus Bakery. I love Italian style cappuccino’s. For me Circus Bakery had the best cappuccino I’ve had in Paris. That cinnamon bun is fantastic! I don’t like sourdough either but their breads are fantastic. They are making pizzas in the afternoon and evenings now as well.
I liked them so much I was stopping by twice a day. I was staying in an apartment next to Odette that had a view of the Nôtre Dame so I was just about 30 seconds from Circus Bakery.

replies.textDisplay: Sorry to hear that. Food poisoning while traveling is terrible. I got food poisoning from a restaurant in Rome from pancetta. The late Anthony Bourdain wrote that he would never eat mussels at a restaurant unless he knew the chef personally. On the other hand, I've eaten mussels in dozens of restaurants in multiple countries and never had a problem. I plan to eat mussels next month "en Bretagne." Wish me luck.

comments.textDisplay: I love the 5th so much! There are two places that I kind of fell in love with while we stayed there. One was the Abbey Bookstore. It’s a tiny little place that makes you feel like you’re in a shoppe in Diagon Alley. All of the books in there look like they are going to topple on you in these narrow little aisles. And second is the plaza outside Sorbonne. It has a few hotels, restaurants, a tabac.... and a Gap LoL.. but the low fountains framing the entrance to the university is a gorgeous view.
